expPurpose: What do you think the experiment was about?
Q1: I can easily tell if someone else wants to enter a conversation.
Q2: I find it difficult to explain to others things that I understand easily, when they don't understand it the first time.
Q3: I really enjoy caring for other people.
Q4: I find it hard to know what to do in a social situation.
Q5: People often tell me that I went too far in driving my point home in a discussion.
Q6: It doesn't bother me too much if I am late meeting a friend.
Q7: Friendships and relationships are just too difficult, so I tend not to bother with them.
Q8: I often find it difficult to judge if something is rude or polite.
Q9: In a conversation, I tend to focus on my own thoughts rather than on what my listener might be thinking.
Q10: When I was a child, I enjoyed cutting up worms to see what would happen.
Q11: I can pick up quickly if someone says one thing but means another.
Q12: It is hard for me to see why some things upset people so much.
Q13: I find it easy to put myself in somebody else's shoes.
Q14: I am good at predicting how someone will feel.
Q15: I am quick to spot when someone in a group is feeling awkward or uncomfortable.
Q16: If I say something that someone else is offended by, I think that that's their problem, not mine.
Q17: If anyone asked me if I like their haricut, I would reply truthfully, even if I didn't like it.
Q18: I can't always see why someone should have felt offended by a remark.
Q19: Seeing people cry doesn't really upset me.
Q20: I am very blunt, which some people take to be rudeness, even though this is unintentional.
Q21: I don't tend to find social situations confusing
Q22: Other people tell me I am good at understanding how they are feeling and what they are thinking.
Q23: When I talk to people, I tend to talk about their experiences rather than my own.
Q24: It upsets me to see animals in pain.
Q25: I am able to make decisions without being influenced by people's feelings.
Q26: I can easily tell if someone else is interested or bored with what I am saying.
Q27: I get upset if I see people suffering on news programmes.
Q28: Friends usually talk to me about their problems as they say I am very understanding.
Q29: I can sense if I am intruding, even if the other person doesn't tell me.
Q30: People sometimes tell me that I have gone too far with teasing.
Q31: Other people often say that I am insensitive, though I don't always see why.
Q32: If I see a stranger in a group, I think that it is up to them to make an effort to join in.
Q33: I usually stay emotionally detached when watching a film.
Q34: I can tune into how someone else feels rapidly and intuitively.
Q35: I can easily work out what another person might want to talk about.
Q36: I can tell if someone is masking their true emotion.
Q37: I don't consciously work out the rules of social situations.
Q38: I am good at predicting what someone will do.
Q39: I tend to get emotionally involved with a friend's problems.
Q40: I can usually appreciate the other person's viewpoint, even if I don't agree with it.

expPurpose: Our interpretations of annunciations and our ability to recognize the subtle nuisances of accents to determine similarities of the spoken word.

As a Michigander, when I annunciate words the way I would say it opposed to how it would be said by a Canadian, I can notice the Michigan annunciation is spoken in a lower region of my mouth than the Canadian annunciation.
EK2.CanPron.Diff: Canadians have a tendency to use a higher part of their mouth when annunciating certain words.  For example, a Michigander would annunciate the word about, a-bout, where as Canadians would annunciate the same word as a-boot because of their tendency to annunciate their vowels from a higher region of their mouth.
EK4.CanAU.Diff_1_TEXT: A Michigander would annunciate the word about as, a-bout where as a Canadian would annunciate the same word as a-boot.  The same is said for out, which mostly sounds just as it is written when a Michigander annunciates it, but sounds more like oot when a Canadian says it.

expPurpose: I think it was about recognizing differences in dialects that are similar or close in location, but I'm sure there's more to it than that.
LingExp: Have taken a few communications classes not necessarily related to linguistics but sort of. I have also taken 6 years on Japanese classes and studied in Japan for a semester.
SK1.WhereStandard: Middle Eastern US or West Coast
EK1.CanSpeak.Diff: As a Michigander, I can pick out Canadians by their speech, but only a few things consciously stand out to me such as the 'ou' combination of vowels sounding different and some other vowel combinations that I don't consciously pick up.
EK2.CanPron.Diff: As I said in the previous section, vowel combinations tend to be different in my experience. I don't know a lot of Canadians, but whenever I drive home from GR to Port Huron, I hear the differences very plainly on the radio and sometimes in person as Port Huron is only 1-4 miles away from Canada at any given location. The 'ou' vowel combo and 'a' in words with consonance on each side clearly sound different to me. Some Michiganders who have lived in other places, like my Grandma, pronounce places incorrectly (at least according to me) like "Port Huron" pronounced as "Porchurine."
EK4.CanAU.Diff_1_TEXT: Michiganders pronounce the 'ou' sounds more like "ah u," like "ah-oh-t" for the word "out." Canadians seem to pronounce it more like "oot." At least in my experience.
ME1.TVShows: Trailer Park Boys,How I Met Your Mother

expPurpose: Perhaps the perception of speakers to linguistic vowel shifts such as the Great Lakes Cities Shift and Canadian Fronting of vowels.
LingExp: My wife has a Master's in English translation and I'm generally just fascinated by linguistics and particularly my own (strong by account of others) Michiganaccent.
EK1.CanSpeak.Diff: Canadians tend to have different diphthongs. House - About - Processor etc. The vowels can also be fronted and raised when compared to Michiganders. I would also expect to have some Great Lakes Cities shift when compared to someone from say Manitoba or Alberta. I'm personally not so great at hearing the shift in the wild, but it drives my wife, whose second language is English, up a proverbial wall when she hears a strong Cities Shift accent.
EK2.CanPron.Diff: As I previously mentioned, I would expect a Canadian to have some different diphthongs (about - house - process etc.) but also to front and raise their vowels. Michiganders may exhibit the Northern Cities shift that isn't as prevalent in Canada.
EK4.CanAU.Diff_1_TEXT: The dipthong is elongated and raised. Ouuuut, Houuuuse compared to how I would say the word.

expPurpose: Seeing how well people can tell the difference between Northern US accents and Canadian accents.
EK1.CanSpeak.Diff: The lines get blurrier the further north you do in Michigan, but generally I think that Canadians tend to skip hard consonants at the end of words like "t" and "d" more harshly than Michiganders do. There is also a distinct difference in the ways that vowels like "o" and "u" are pronounced in the middle of words, but I'm not sure how I would describe the difference in words.
EK2.CanPron.Diff: Like I said before, consonants and vowels are pronounced differently the further north you go. I think that Canadians generally have a softer pronunciation which skips many ending consonants and accentuates mid-word vowels. Michiganders do the same but to a lesser extent.
EK4.CanAU.Diff_1_TEXT: The "o" and "u" in Canadian English is higher pitched and softer than in Michigan English. In Michigan English those letters are pronounced flatly and almost "nasally."
